            <p rendition="simple_centre">SUMMARY OF CONCLUSIONS</p>
            <p>1. <gloss target="#t_CIA_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recrGZfmTCYX9A5jf">CIA</orgName>
                </gloss>’s assessment is that <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl"
                    >Morocco</placeName> is facing serious problems, largely because of the
                stagnating economic situation, the continuing <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recD8UEyBEWnzRQtf">Sahara conflict</rs>, and the ineffective
                leadership. These trends may get worse, with serious consequences for <rs
                    type="compound-subject" corresp="recsWOnchx3QJo5qE">U.S.-Moroccan
                relations</rs>. It was agreed that the U.S. has a serious interest in <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> and in cooperation with King
                    <persName corresp="rec8m8MetQlvwXVeh">Hassan</persName>. <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName>’s generally moderate stand on
                    <placeName corresp="recJAi0OpNdSuYev5">Middle East</placeName> and African
                issues is a particularly valuable asset. While taking steps <pb facs="0116" n="95"
                    xml:id="pg_95"/> to strengthen <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recsWOnchx3QJo5qE">U.S.-Moroccan relations</rs>, however, we should be
                mindful of our important economic interests in <placeName
                    corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> and of the fluid leadership
                situation there.</p>
            <p>2. The Moroccans have requested $6 million worth of <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recSkg5rdjWW1fsS7">spare parts</rs> for the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rec3QSbxhrMctVdHq">F–5 aircraft</rs>. Until now, this package has been
                held up because of disagreement on the use of the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rec3QSbxhrMctVdHq">F–5</rs> in the Sahara. All agencies, with the
                exception of <gloss target="#t_ACDA_1">
                    <orgName corresp="reckjQkUajOv3dbTz">ACDA</orgName>
                </gloss>, now believe we should go forward with this request. <gloss
                    target="#t_ACDA_1">
                    <orgName corresp="reckjQkUajOv3dbTz">ACDA</orgName>
                </gloss>’s dissent is based on the belief that the spare parts will not
                significantly affect the military situation confronting <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> and will constitute a technical
                violation of the <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recGwJdP0JlBPSbVG"
                    >U.S.-Moroccan military assistance agreement</rs>. <orgName
                    corresp="recjQ97iMHKp6vwlA">Defense</orgName> and <orgName
                    corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">State</orgName> have determined that the spare parts
                would not constitute such a violation. <orgName corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM"
                    >Congressional</orgName> consultations on this case have indicated general
                support, with the exception of Senator <persName corresp="recV8EadpcMRnS42U"
                    >McGovern</persName>.</p>
            <p>3. <orgName corresp="recjQ97iMHKp6vwlA">Defense</orgName> and <gloss
                    target="#t_JCS_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">JCS</orgName>
                </gloss> will quietly examine other military items which might be of a particular
                help to the Moroccans in the present circumstances. <orgName
                    corresp="recjQ97iMHKp6vwlA">Defense</orgName> believes that inadequate
                communications equipment and surveillance may be the major problems currently
                confronting the Moroccan forces. Recommendations should be available within several
                weeks.</p>
            <p>4. All participants felt that the <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recD8UEyBEWnzRQtf">Sahara conflict</rs> could not be resolved
                militarily. At some point, a political settlement will be essential. It is not clear
                that the time is right for a settlement, nor is there consensus on what possible
                role the U.S. might play. Consequently, a small study group will be formed to
                examine diplomatic strategies for beginning the process of accommodation between
                    <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> and <placeName
                    corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> concerning the Sahara.<note
                    n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d38fn2">See <ref target="#d239">Document
                    239</ref>.</note> This group will also explore means for channeling more
                economic assistance to <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName>,
                and in particular a resumption of assistance from <placeName
                    corresp="recXEA0LEpEd93tFt">Saudi Arabia</placeName>.</p>
